-- Aviva, Dana Petroleum, GlaxoSmithKline, Shell: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- Ben Martin
-- 2010-07-02T06:29:10Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-01/dana-petroleum-plc-glaxosmithkline-shell-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  
 The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  fell 111.12, or 2.3 percent,
to 4,805.75. The  FTSE All-Share Index  declined 2.3 percent and
Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  fell 2.9 percent.  
 Aviva Plc  (AV/ LN): The insurer is expecting to increase
the amount of capital it generates to 1.3 billion pounds ($2
billion) this year, the Financial Times reported, citing Chief
Financial Officer  Patrick Regan . The shares dropped 2.6 percent
to 305.8 pence.  
 BHP Billiton Plc  (BLT LN),  Rio Tinto Plc  (RIO LN): Mining
companies may be active after Australian Prime Minister  Julia Gillard  scaled back a proposed tax on the industry to win their
support, easing concern economic growth will slow and depriving
the opposition of a key election platform. BHP lost 3.4 percent
to 1,694.5 pence. Rio Tinto declined 2.2 percent to 2,904.5
pence.  
 Dana Petroleum Plc  (DNX LN): The Scottish explorer focused
on Europe and Africa said it received a “very preliminary
approach which may or may not lead to an offer” for the
company. The shares advanced 3.7 percent to 1,177 pence.  
 GlaxoSmithKline Plc  (GSK LN): The drugmaker will pay Genmab
A/S 90 million pounds to take over development of the Arzerra
treatment for autoimmune diseases that the companies had been
working on together. The stock fell 2.9 percent to 1,109.5
pence.  
 Royal Dutch Shell Plc  (RDSA LN): Europe’s largest oil
company is offering for sale its interest in undeveloped U.K.
licenses that include the Bacchus field, according to a
Schlumberger Ltd. oil-services marketing website. The shares
declined 4.5 percent to 1,624 pence.  
 Travis Perkins Plc  (TPK LN): The builder said it now sees a
result for the six months to June 30 “ahead of management
expectations.” The shares lost 3.3 percent to 709 pence.  
